00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.657
Let's play just a little bit of
his "Eine kleine

00:02:10.657 --> 00:02:12.292
Nachtmusik,"
"A Little Night

00:02:12.292 --> 00:02:13.000
Music."
 

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.120
It's a sort of divertimento,
evening music for

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:17.229
entertainment.
 

00:02:17.229 --> 00:02:19.520
Let's listen to a little bit
about it and then I'll say

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:20.030
something.
 

00:02:20.030 --> 00:02:49.340
&gt;
 

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:52.770
What can we say about that
music?

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:54.319
Well, we've talked a lot about
this before.

00:02:54.319 --> 00:02:55.599
It's very patterned.
 

00:02:55.599 --> 00:02:56.940
It's very symmetrical.
 

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:57.940
It's balanced.
 

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:00.508
We have antecedent and
consequent phrases and they come

00:03:00.508 --> 00:03:02.460
in the music with the classical
period.

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:03.479
What about the orchestra?
 

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:08.125
Well, it's rather small in that
it's dominated principally by

00:03:08.125 --> 00:03:09.210
the strings.
 

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:11.893
And we had a couple of
Listening Exercises where we'd

00:03:11.893 --> 00:03:14.937
see the strings play the themes
and then the woodwinds maybe

00:03:14.937 --> 00:03:17.258
come back to echo them or to
answer them.

00:03:17.258 --> 00:03:20.439
But most of the musical
material is getting presented by

00:03:20.439 --> 00:03:21.250
the strings.
 

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:25.336
The texture--well,
the texture is rather thin here

00:03:25.336 --> 00:03:30.008
because it's not a very big
orchestra, a thin texture.

00:03:30.008 --> 00:03:32.910
And what can we say also about
the texture?

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:36.997
Well, it tends to be rather
polyphonic, homophonic or

00:03:36.997 --> 00:03:38.020
monophonic?
 

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:41.199
Well, in that case, homophonic.
 

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:44.160
Basically, you got a melody
plus accompaniment.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:47.163
And we could also
say--something that we've talked

00:03:47.163 --> 00:03:50.720
about--that this music has a
kind of rhetorical strategy to

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:51.150
it.
 

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:52.810
We have this idea of music.
 

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.930
It sounds like a melody,
it sounds like a theme,

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:58.720
or music that sounds like it's
coming between themes,

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:00.818
of leading us somewhere,
transitional music,

00:04:00.818 --> 00:04:03.469
music that may be a contrasting
theme,

00:04:03.469 --> 00:04:05.908
music that ends a section.
 

00:04:05.908 --> 00:04:09.183
So it's music that does
something, music that's trying

00:04:09.183 --> 00:04:12.830
to get us from point A to point
B and point C and so on,

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:14.710
so it's a sort of rhetorical
music,

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:18.350
teleological music if you will.
 

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:20.360
Okay.
 

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:24.670
Now, let's turn to a piece of
romantic music.

00:04:24.670 --> 00:04:28.764
And before we do that I'm going
to say a thing or two about this

00:04:28.764 --> 00:04:29.870
romantic music.
 

00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:33.531
It's a piece by Tchaikovsky
from his Romeo and

00:04:33.531 --> 00:04:36.125
Juliet,
and I think we have the titles

00:04:36.125 --> 00:04:38.925
of the pieces that we'll be
listening to on the board up

00:04:38.925 --> 00:04:40.833
there today--
so from his Romeo and

00:04:40.833 --> 00:04:41.379
Juliet.
 

00:04:41.379 --> 00:04:44.870
And you've probably heard this
music before because it used to

00:04:44.870 --> 00:04:47.790
be--a lot of it used to be used
in cartoon music.

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:51.851
Anytime there was a love scene
this particular music would come

00:04:51.851 --> 00:04:52.180
on.
 

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:54.019
So what are its qualities here?
 

00:04:54.019 --> 00:04:56.896
Well, first of all,
it has a long,

00:04:56.896 --> 00:05:00.211
sweeping melody here in
romantic music,

00:05:00.211 --> 00:05:05.879
a long, sweeping melody that is
rather asymmetrical in shape.

00:05:05.879 --> 00:05:09.271
Instead of having neat units of
two plus two plus two,

00:05:09.271 --> 00:05:12.661
it could go on over bars or
maybe it'll be a seven-bar

00:05:12.661 --> 00:05:14.709
phrase, something like that.
 

00:05:14.709 --> 00:05:17.560
So the melodies tend to be long;
they tend to be asymmetrical.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:21.401
Rhythm--think about rhythm in
the music that we've been

00:05:21.401 --> 00:05:22.470
listening to.
 

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:28.411
My paradigm here is the
beginning of the Brandenburg

00:05:28.411 --> 00:05:34.470
Fifth Concerto Grosso,
in which the rhythm starts out

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:37.500
&gt;.
 

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:38.610
It's very regular.
 

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:41.428
It's like a machine gun,
almost, or a sewing machine,

00:05:41.428 --> 00:05:43.759
or some kind of repetitive
process there.

00:05:43.759 --> 00:05:49.848
When we get into the classical
period, rhythm is somewhat more

00:05:49.848 --> 00:05:55.639
relaxed but it is still a
pattern, &gt;

00:05:55.639 --> 00:05:59.040
but here, with this music in
the romantic period,

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:02.439
the themes are not only long
and asymmetrical;

00:06:02.439 --> 00:06:06.831
the rhythms don't seem to shake
out in patterns that allow us to

00:06:06.831 --> 00:06:10.180
tap our feet or allow us to
conduct it easily.

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:12.740
So we have ties over bars.
 

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:13.829
We have lots of syncopation.
 

00:06:13.829 --> 00:06:18.697
We have irregular phrasing,
somewhat irregular metrical

00:06:18.697 --> 00:06:20.410
patterns as well.
 

00:06:20.410 --> 00:06:23.714
Tempo--we've talked a little
bit about this before and this

00:06:23.714 --> 00:06:25.709
idea of tempo rubato
here.

00:06:25.709 --> 00:06:28.494
In romantic music,
we get wild swings of tempo in

00:06:28.494 --> 00:06:32.379
that it can be coming along at a
regular pace and then slow way,

00:06:32.379 --> 00:06:35.413
way down and then speed up to
get back on track and slow down

00:06:35.413 --> 00:06:36.019
and so on.
 

00:06:36.019 --> 00:06:41.245
And this is part and parcel of
the romantic aesthetic in the

00:06:41.245 --> 00:06:46.028
sense that it tends to swing
wildly from one extreme to

00:06:46.028 --> 00:06:49.600
another,
wildly in terms of rhythm and

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:52.019
wildly in terms of dynamics.
 

00:06:52.019 --> 00:06:54.281
We can go from very,
very quiet to very,

00:06:54.281 --> 00:06:56.720
very loud in a way that Mozart
couldn't.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:59.139
Remember we were talking about
Mozart's piano,

00:06:59.139 --> 00:07:02.204
which weighed about one tenth
of what this piano weighs up

00:07:02.204 --> 00:07:02.689
here.
 

00:07:02.689 --> 00:07:04.740
This piano probably weighs
about eight hundred pounds.

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:07.769
Mozart's probably weighed about
one hundred pounds.

00:07:07.769 --> 00:07:09.399
So this is a much bigger
instrument.

00:07:09.399 --> 00:07:12.250
You can play very quietly on it
or you can make a huge sound on

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:14.310
it;
same thing with the orchestra

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:16.899
and we'll come back to that
point today.

00:07:16.899 --> 00:07:18.709
Mozart had a modest orchestra.
 

00:07:18.709 --> 00:07:21.500
Mahler at the end of this
period had a huge orchestra.

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:24.399
So this allows for these wild
swings.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:27.646
The romantic period is sort of
a bipolar period,

00:07:27.646 --> 00:07:30.478
I guess, in terms of music in
that regard.

00:07:30.478 --> 00:07:31.100
Okay.
 

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:34.303
Having said that,
let's listen to what we might

00:07:34.303 --> 00:07:37.788
call a prototypical moment in
romantic music out of

00:07:37.788 --> 00:07:41.550
Tchaikovsky's overture to
Romeo and Juliet.

00:07:41.550 --> 00:08:04.470
&gt;
 

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:09.637
Now it starts to build,
a little bit of melodic

00:08:09.637 --> 00:08:16.040
sequence working up here,
&gt;

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:19.500
reaching higher and higher each
time.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:52.928
&gt;
 

00:08:52.928 --> 00:08:55.029
So it's a really remarkable
passage.

00:08:55.029 --> 00:08:58.424
It's made possible by this
newly enlarged orchestra so

00:08:58.424 --> 00:09:01.500
let's talk about this orchestra
for a moment,

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:04.385
and we're going to reference
here our four "food

00:09:04.385 --> 00:09:07.440
types" or our four
instrumental groups for the--

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:11.548
for classical art music,
starting with the strings.

00:09:11.548 --> 00:09:14.950
We don't really have any new
instruments here in the romantic

00:09:14.950 --> 00:09:15.460
period.
 

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:19.101
We still have basically the
four string instruments of

00:09:19.101 --> 00:09:21.573
violin, viola,
cello and double bass,

00:09:21.573 --> 00:09:23.428
but they are different.
 

00:09:23.428 --> 00:09:26.288
They're different from the
instrument that Mozart was

00:09:26.288 --> 00:09:26.840
playing.
 

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:27.649
What happened?
 

00:09:27.649 --> 00:09:30.629
Well, in the nineteenth century
the construction of the violin

00:09:30.629 --> 00:09:32.389
was changed rather
significantly,

00:09:32.389 --> 00:09:35.509
and I think I could just hold
my hand out here,

00:09:35.509 --> 00:09:37.070
maybe demonstrate this kind of
thing.

00:09:37.070 --> 00:09:40.958
First of all,
there was a higher bridge put

00:09:40.958 --> 00:09:41.700
on it.
 

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.144
If you have the bridge holding
up the strings in an

00:09:44.144 --> 00:09:46.639
eighteenth-century violin it
might be like that--

00:09:46.639 --> 00:09:48.059
a nineteenth-century violin
like that,

00:09:48.059 --> 00:09:49.080
higher bridge.
 

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:53.120
That allows you to have more
tension.

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:58.246
It puts more tension on the
entire instrument and at the

00:09:58.246 --> 00:10:02.153
same time,
the strings that had been used,

00:10:02.153 --> 00:10:05.227
which were made of--
anybody have a sense of what

00:10:05.227 --> 00:10:07.679
violin strings in the eighteenth
century were made of?

00:10:07.679 --> 00:10:10.000
Chelsea.
 

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.120
Student: Catgut.
 

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:12.669
Prof: Catgut sometimes,
yes.

00:10:12.669 --> 00:10:14.419
Yes, animal lovers, catgut.
 

00:10:14.419 --> 00:10:16.678
More normally sheep gut. Okay?
 

00:10:16.678 --> 00:10:20.417
So sheep gut,
and that wouldn't--the tension

00:10:20.417 --> 00:10:25.283
that could be put on that was
not as great as if you were

00:10:25.283 --> 00:10:27.370
using a wire string.
 

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:30.931
So in the nineteenth century,
technological advances,

00:10:30.931 --> 00:10:32.711
wire strings,
more tension,

00:10:32.711 --> 00:10:34.559
higher bridge,
and to--well,

00:10:34.559 --> 00:10:37.298
also the fingerboard was
extended.

00:10:37.298 --> 00:10:40.254
It's longer so oftentimes with
a Stradivarius they'd chop off

00:10:40.254 --> 00:10:41.980
the fingerboard and put
another--

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:45.320
a new fingerboard on it and put
it all back together again.

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:47.000
What else?
 

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.080
I know I'm missing one other
important thing.

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.340
Well, maybe that will have to
do it for the moment,

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:59.577
and what we'll end up with--oh,
I know.

00:10:59.577 --> 00:11:00.600
The bow.
 

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:02.567
If you look at an
eighteenth-century bow and go to

00:11:02.567 --> 00:11:04.977
